FT  19 OCT 93 / International Company News: Macmillan venture charge hits
McGraw-Hill profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MCGRAW-HILL, the US publisher and broadcaster, has blamed a extraordinary
charge for a third-quarter net loss of Dollars 91.9m, against profits of
Dollars 59.3m last time, agencies report from New York.
Without the Dollars 160.8m charge, related to the acquisition of partner
Macmillan's share of a joint venture, there would have been net profits of
Dollars 68.93m, a rise of 16.2 per cent.
The company said its Standard &amp; Poor's ratings group, other financial
services businesses, international book publishing, and the Macmillan/
McGraw-Hill School Publishing joint venture all performed well in the
quarter.
The company is buying the half interest in the joint venture owned by the
late Mr Robert Maxwell.
Sales at the group were up slightly to Dollars 554.9m, compared with Dollars
534m for the same period last year.
McGraw-Hill said revenue in its financial services division rose 13.6 per
cent, while operating profit was up 18.4 per cent.
Information and Publication Services revenue fell 5.1 per cent due to
softness in the construction and advertising-based markets, the company
said.
However, cost-controls and improved results at some of its publications
helped produce a 14.6 per cent increase in operating profits in the
division.
The company said its share of the Macmillan/McGraw-Hill joint venture school
publishing company profits rose 10.2 per cent in the quarter.
It said it would recognise for the first time all the costs associated with
the venture, which normally shows a loss in the fourth quarter.
</TEXT>
