FT  19 OCT 93 / International Company News: Bundaberg bids for two
Queensland sugar mills
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BUNDABERG Sugar Company, part of the UK's Tate &amp; Lyle sugar group, is making
a ADollars 87m (USDollars 57.6m) cash offer for two sugar mills in north
Queensland. The mills, which are independent of each other, are
co-operatives and owned by local sugar cane growers.
Bundaberg has proposed to pay just under ADollars 50m for the Tully Mill and
about ADollars 37m for the South Johnstone Mill. It would then spend a
further Dollars 13m on the mills over a two-year period, taking its
investment to ADollars 100m.
However, directors at both mills recommended that the offers be rejected as
inadequate, and said they were hiring legal and financial advisers to
provide further appraisals. Mr Dennis Stevens, general manager of the South
Johnstone Mill, told local news agencies that the company had advised its
270 shareholders that the offer was too low.
Meanwhile, Tully Sugar said its board had decided the offer was
'significantly inadequate as it values our company at less than Dollars 50m.
Our board recommended to shareholders that they take no action,' the company
added.
The offers are conditional on 90 per cent minimum acceptance and to Foreign
Investment Review Board approval. Formal documents, outlining the offer, are
expected to be registered in about one week and circulated to shareholders
shortly afterwards.
</TEXT>
