<PROFILE>_AN-DJSC5AFBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931019
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / International Company News: BNP shares open at 18% premium
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Banque Nationale de Paris (BNP), the French government's first
privatisation candidate, yesterday closed at FFr283.90, an 18 per cent
premium over the original FFr240 offer price, at the end of the first day of
official trading on the Paris stock market.
BNP's shares opened at FFr277.20, immediately breaching the 15 per cent
trading limit for the first day of dealings. The shares were suspended for
15 minutes, only to resume trading at FFr282.50. They then rose to a high of
FFr285.90 before settling down to the closing price.
The enthusiastic response to the BNP issue caused chaos on the Paris market
as brokers were swamped with orders for shares.
Dealers estimated that some 2.25m BNP shares changed hands in the first two
hours of trading and that around 4m shares were traded in the course of the
day, representing 3.4 per cent of the bank's equity.
'It's been crazy, just crazy,' said one Paris banking analyst. 'It's almost
like London used to be during the Thatcherite privatisations back in the
1980s.'
The BNP issue, which was priced far lower than analysts had expected, was
heavily oversubscribed by both institutional and individual investors.
The French government was forced to reduce dramatically the allocation of
equity to institutions, to try to satisfy demand from the public. However,
it still rationed the number of shares given to individual investors.
Banking analysts attributed the strong demand for BNP shares to heavy buying
from institutions that had been disappointed by their allocations in the
original issue.
Some individual investors seized their chance to make quick profits by
selling their shares.
'The offer price was so low that subscribing for BNP shares almost looked
like a licence to make money,' commented another analyst. 'But the French
government wanted to make sure that the first privatisation was a success -
and it's done it.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
