<PROFILE>_AN-DJSC5AD2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931019
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Rhone-Poulenc named as next in French sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RHONE-POULENC, France's flagship chemicals group, will be the next to be
sold in the government's ambitious privatisation programme, the French
economy ministry said yesterday. The sale is expected within weeks,
depending on market conditions.
The announcement ended speculation that the government would capitalise on
the successful privatisation of Banque Nationale de Paris by bringing
forward the sale of its 50 per cent stake in Elf-Aquitaine, the oil group.
The privatisation of Elf would raise about FFr50bn (Pounds 5.8bn) compared
with the FFr15bn forecast from the sale of the government's 43 per cent
stake in Rhone-Poulenc.
Elf, which will be the third of 21 public sector companies to be privatised,
is expected to be sold early next year. Mr Edmond Alphandery, economy
minister, said Rhone-Poulenc was better prepared than Elf for privatisation.
The structure of the sale is expected to be similar to that of BNP, with
separate tranches for individual and institutional investors. The government
and Rhone-Poulenc will also create a core of stable shareholders, to
represent between 25 per cent and 35 per cent of the company's capital.
Mr Jean-Rene Fourtou, Rhone-Poulenc chairman, is confident of a successful
privatisation as the partial sale in January, when the state sold 10 per
cent of the shares, was oversubscribed.
Observers in Paris also expected a smooth sale. 'The sharp rise in BNP's
share price yesterday will have whetted the appetite of individual
investors,' said one analyst. He said that shares in Rhone-Poulenc were also
likely to be attractively priced to maintain the momentum of the
privatisation programme.
However, Rhone-Poulenc is suffering from difficult markets. In the
first-half, net profits fell by about 11 per cent to FFr1.37bn, reflecting
depressed conditions in the bulk chemicals and fibres markets. The company's
healthcare operations, which last year generated 73 per cent of group
operating profits, have been hit by reforms in Germany and Italy.
BNP shares suspended, Page 20
