<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Trafalgar warns on profits: Shares fall as rights issue is
confirmed; More provisions likely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SHARE price of Trafalgar House fell 11 1/2 p to close at 85p yesterday
after the construction and engineering group announced plans to raise up to
Pounds 400m in a rights issue and made a profits warning.
Analysts had pencilled in a profit of about Pounds 50m before tax and
provisions for the year to September 30. Profit estimates were reduced after
yesterday's announcement and the provisions figure raised.
Trafalgar House said it was getting independent valuations of its property.
As a result, it expected to make further substantial provisions in addition
to the Pounds 100m taken at the halfway stage.
One of the properties likely to be written down is London's Ritz Hotel,
currently valued at Pounds 85m, which the group has been trying to sell.
Another is the Emerald oil rig.
The convertible preference share issue will be the group's third cash call
in two years. Mr Simon Keswick, chairman, said that the growing engineering
and construction division required a stronger capital base.
Hongkong Land, which has a 25 per cent stake, confirmed that it would
subscribe for its full share of the issue, details of which will be
announced in December with annual results.
Mr Allan Gormly, chief executive, said that net debt had fallen below Pounds
300m by the end of September, and the group should be ungeared after the
rights issue.
It confirmed that the final dividend would be 2p per ordinary share, to be
paid from reserves. Mr Keswick said the rights issue would be made through
preference shares because investors were entitled to feel confident they
would get a return on their money.
The board has also arranged new credit and bonding facilities with the HSBC
Group. Mr Gormly said this would simplify the group's complex financial
arrangements.
He is stepping down as chief executive next August to become the chairman of
Royal Insurance Holdings. He will remain on Trafalgar House's board as a
non-executive director.
His replacement will be Mr Nigel Rich, 47, managing director of Jardine
Matheson Holdings, which controls Hongkong Land.
Trafalgar also said that Mr John Olsen, chief executive of Cunard and
managing director of the group's shipping and hotels division, had joined
the board.
