<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Assignment: The Price of Gold (BBC 2, 7.45) investigates the terrible
effects of mercury poisoning on humans and the environment in Brazil's
mining villages, the country's poorest regions. Mercury imports have been
banned by the government but the valuable income from goldmining has meant
far from stringent application of the ban.
Auberon Waugh voices his opinions of the Booker Prize on tonight's C4
culture series, Without Walls (9.00). He is followed by Peter Wayne, a
long-term prisoner who for 12 years has been researching 18th century
architect Thomas Archer.
The search to identify the genes responsible for causing certain cancers
proceeds apace. In the informative series Cracking the Code: The Cancer
Hunters (BBC 2, 9.30), David Suzuki looks at promising research into genes
which cause, among other cancers, a rare hereditary form of breast cancer.
A new 10-part series, Children's Hospital (BBC 1, 8.00) is about life as it
really is on the wards at the Sheffield Children's Hospital. We are promised
heart-warming and heart-breaking stories.
</TEXT>
