<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Chambers urge aid for industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT should take a more interventionist role in manufacturing
industry, Birmingham Chamber of Commerce, the largest chamber in Britain,
said yesterday.
The chamber said the government should offer tax breaks to investors,
low-cost finance for new companies and enhanced credit guarantees for
exporters.
It said that without such state aid the weakness of Britain's manufacturing
sector would impede export-led growth.
The document, setting out the long-term needs of Britain's 'industrial
heartlands', precedes a national survey this week by the British Chambers of
Commerce which is expected to show that many companies doubt that the
recovery can be sustained while the recession in continental Europe worsens.
Although the survey is also understood to show a significant upturn in
domestic demand in the past quarter, the Birmingham Chamber fears this is
mainly through growing demand for services rather than manufacturing.
Mr Tony Bradley, head of policy at the Birmingham chamber, said: 'In the
absence of a strong manufacturing sector, a domestic recovery led by
consumers and services will only reproduce the inflationary boom-bust cycle
and will not lay the foundations for sustainable medium-term growth.'
To offset the structural faults in the economy, the chamber advocates:
Abolition of capital gains tax for investors who retain their shares in
companies for more than five years.
New financial support for exporters through export credit guarantees.
An extension of tax relief on training expenditure.
A reduction in 'regulatory burdens imposed on industry'.
'More flexible and responsive financing packages' for small and medium-sized
companies.
Mr Bradley said almost 30 per cent of manufacturing companies in the
Midlands had shed jobs in the past year and 30 per cent expected to make
further cuts.
Manufacturing Industry in the West Midlands, Birmingham Chamber of Commerce
&amp; Industry, 75 Harborne Road, Birmingham B15 3DH.
</TEXT>
