<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Drive on benefits 'saved Pounds 558m'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER LILLEY, social security secretary, told the Commons yesterday that
record 'fraud savings' of Pounds 558m were made last year.
Mr Lilley said the Benefits Agency caught more than 270,000 people
'cheating' the social security system. He suggested that doctors would be
likely to welcome new procedures to determine eligibility for invalidity
benefit.
Replying to protests by Labour MPs, Mr Lilley said he had never criticised
doctors for the rapid growth in the numbers being paid invalidity benefit.
During the past 15 years the number of claimants had nearly trebled, while
the expenditure involved had more than trebled in real terms.
Dr Charles Goodson-Wickes, Conservative MP for Wimbledon, said the system
was perceived by many to be subject to abuse.
