<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Employers criticised on training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INDUSTRIAL SOCIETY yesterday criticised the 'astonishing failure' of
many employers to check the value of the staff training that they pay for.
According to the society's quarterly survey, employers spend an average of
Pounds 492 per head on training, with each employee spending a total of just
over four days a year being trained.
However, only 36 per cent of personnel directors questioned said their
organisation defined objectives for each training and development programme
before the programme began. The survey covered about one-third of the
society's 12,000 member organisations.
The majority simply did not know if objectives were fixed, indicating, said
the society, that if such a policy existed it was unlikely to be properly
carried out.
With the exception of questionnaires, most organisations did very little to
discover employees' views on how effective their training had been. This
made it very difficult to ascertain if training programmes had been
successful.
Many employers were 'wasting precious investment' in skills, said Mr Andrew
Forrest, the society's human resources director. Organisations needed to
take two vital steps to ensure the maximum return on their investment in
skills.
'Training has to be closely linked to business objectives, not a sideshow
with little connection to corporate strategy,' he said. 'Employers need
systems to evaluate the aims of training before it happens and the
effectiveness of training after it happens.'
The Investment in People initiative, administered by training and enterprise
councils, is intended to help companies link their training more effectively
to their business plan.
Mr Forrest said a surge in support for the scheme was an encouraging sign
that organisations were trying to tighten control of their training
activity. Tecs were becoming increasingly effective at serving business
locally, with IIP one of the topics they were most often contacted about.
Training Trends 10; Pounds 25; Industrial Society, 49 Calthorpe Road,
Birmingham B15 1TH.
</TEXT>
