<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Minister tries to calm fears on councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S new policy for local government reorganisation will not
lead to district councils taking over the functions of county councils, Mr
David Curry, local government minister, said yesterday.
Instead, single-tier authorities would be created by merging adjacent
district authorities which would be given wider powers.
Mr Curry told a conference of the Association of District Councils: 'It is
certainly not our intention that existing district councils will become
unitary councils. I wish to make sure that the new councils can effectively
tackle the problems of dealing with strategic issues.'
He said that creating a mass of small unitary authorities would lead to the
creation of new joint bodies, and added: 'If you do that, you might as well
keep the counties in the first place.'
Mr Curry refused to be drawn on an ideal size for the new authorities.
Mr Martin Easteal, chief executive of the Local Government Commission, said
he expected the new unitary authorities to have populations of between
150,000 and 250,000.
Mr Curry made clear to the commission that the government did not expect it
to recommend maintaining the status quo of two-tier county and district
councils.
He said: 'If we were to be invited to do that we might well decide we wished
to revisit those recommendations.'
Mr Curry's statement followed last week's poll conducted for the commission
by MORI in County Durham, which found an overall majority of the voters
favouring the status quo.
Sir John Banham, chairman of the commission, described the views of the
local electorate as 'the jury' for any proposals.
He said he was 'most unlikely to discount the clearly expressed view of a
representative sample of the people of Durham who have had a chance to look
very closely at a range of unitary councils and are clearly unimpressed by
them'.
However, Mr Curry said: 'If I wanted the entire reorganisation to be
determined by MORI, I would have asked them to carry it out in the first
place.'
He added that local authorities should now take the initiative in producing
options for mergers between councils which could then be evaluated by Sir
John.
If they did so, he said, they could 'lead public opinion'. The alternative,
he said, was 'falling back on the status quo'.
</TEXT>
