<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Business and local strategy surveyed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE action is needed to convince managers and financial institutions of the
commercial benefits of corporate community involvement, a survey by Opinion
Leader Research shows today.
The survey results will be launched at tonight's annual meeting of Business
in the Community's Per Cent Club - a group of business leaders pledged to
regular support for community activities - which will be addressed by Mr
John Major, the prime minister.
It shows that while many companies believe community involvement can
contribute to business performance through better competitive advantage,
public image, employee relations and customer loyalty, opinions of its value
differ among different sections of the business community.
While chairmen and chief executives had a broad understanding and acceptance
of the importance of the subject, says the survey, senior commercial
managers had a 'less clear understanding of, and a reduced commitment to,
community involvement.'
There was a need for companies to involve a wider management team in
community investment programmes. as a 'credible and essential part of the
core business strategy.'
</TEXT>
