<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Gas monopoly 'keeps tariffs up'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE early abolition of British Gas's monopoly in supplying the mainly
residential market could lead to annual savings on gas bills of 8 per cent,
or Pounds 26 per household, according to a report issued yesterday by 12
independent gas companies.
The 12 reject the possibility that the removal of the monopoly could lead to
a rise of British Gas tariffs for small users, a possibility mentioned in
the recent Monopolies and Mergers Commission report into the future of
British Gas.
They also claim that British Gas's operating overheads are higher than those
of other energy utilities, and that an 'efficient supplier' could operate
with an annual standing charge of Pounds 32 per customer, compared with the
Pounds 36.88 charged by British Gas.
The report said concerns over safety and security of supply would be
addressed by the strict conditions likely to be imposed by the public gas
supplier licence, which the independents would have to obtain before they
could sell gas to households. The Gas Consumers Council welcomed the report.
Mr Ian Powe, council director, said 'If these 12 companies are prepared to
sign up to a strict gas supply licence and still undercut prices then the
sooner the monopoly is abolished the better.'
The independent suppliers, including six joint ventures between regional
electricity companies and Utilicorp UK, the British subsidiary of Utilicorp
of the US, called on Mr Michael Heseltine, trade secretary, to abolish by
1996 the British Gas monopoly on customers using less than 2,500 therms a
year.
The MMC has recommended that the threshold be lowered to 1,500 therms by
1997, and abolished three to five years after the recommended divestment of
British Gas's trading business from its pipeline operations by March 1997.
'It's frustrating to have to wait another four years if you are ready to
provide a service,' Mr Roger Turner, managing director of United Gas, said
yesterday. He called on the Department of Trade and Industry to 'lose no
time in putting the assertions to the test.' British Gas's 30,000 manual
workers at have won a 2.6 per cent pay rise, backdated to January, through
arbitration, the independent Advisory Conciliation and Arbitration Service
said yesterday. The rise, double the offer made by the company, takes the
average basic rate to Pounds 270.75 a week.
</TEXT>
