<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Redwood launches attack on 'yobs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN REDWOOD, the Welsh secretary, last night launched a fierce attack on
what he called the 'yobbish tendency'.
Speaking to the Cardiff Business club, Mr Redwood, who caused a furore in
July with a speech on the social problems caused by single parent families,
said: 'There is in Wales and throughout Britain a revulsion against the
yobbish tendency. We don't want our public buildings defaced by graffiti. We
don't want the fences and roundabouts ripped out of our parks and
playgrounds. We don't want young men shouting and worse on the streets at
night.'
He added: 'The idea that the yobs who do these things have no choice, that
they are creatures of circumstances is nonsense. They are not prisoners of
time and place: they should be prisoners at Her Majesty's pleasure if
nothing else will stop them.'
Mr Redwood drew upon a visit to a primary school for his speech. He said
teachers had asked him how they could be expected to cope with discipline
when parents had lost control of 10-year-olds.
Ten-year-olds, he said, should not be out of control. 'Parents should know
where their children and younger teenagers are after dark. If we don't deal
firmly and quickly with the 10-year-olds, we will have little chance when
they are 15.'
Parents, neighbours and teachers had to take responsibility and the
government had to give a lead which, Mr Redwood said, was what Mr Michael
Howard, the home secretary, was doing.
</TEXT>
