<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Wholesalers lead distribution recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG and better-than-expected increase in sales among UK wholesalers in
September made up for a patchy performance among British retailers and
helped the UK distributive trades as a whole to their best year-on-year
growth in sales since May 1989.
While the Confederation of British Industry expects rising sales in the
retail, wholesale and motor trades this month, its latest survey of all
three distributive trades shows concern at the uneven growth of sales
volumes in Britain's high streets.
The survey, completed by 512 retailers, wholesalers and motor traders
between September 9 and October 6, suggests the three sectors as a whole
should this month have their biggest year-on-year increase in volume sales
for five years.
But the experiences of differing sectors vary widely. Among the 318
retailers polled, grocers, footwear and leather retailers and chemists
reported strong growth in sales volumes in the year to September and expect
further strong increases this month.
Specialist food stores said sales declined in the year to September, as did
retailers of durable household goods. Confectionery sales were unchanged.
Clothing retailers reported only a small increase in sales in the year to
September. This was expressed as a balance of plus 14 percentage points,
representing the difference between the percentage of outlets reporting an
increase in sales over the 12 months and the percentage disclosing a
decline.  This is the method used by the CBI to express sentiment.
Only two classes of retailer reported a year-on-year decline in sales. But
overall, retailers were far less satisfied with last month's volume of sales
than is normal for the time of year.
Grocers and merchants dealing in footwear and leather were the only
retailers to say their sales were better than average last month.
Even among chemists, where the balance of companies reporting sales growth
increased to plus 61 percentage points in September from 37 in August, the
number of companies saying business was poor for the time of year exceeded
those that said it was good by 14 points.
The September survey showed a further strengthening of market power among
the larger retailing chains. The number reporting increased sales volumes
last month exceeded those saying that sales declined by 31 percentage
points. This compared with an average of plus 25 points for the retail
sector as a whole. Single outlet retailers reported an overall drop in sales
compared with last September, with a balance of minus 10 points.
By contrast, the mood among wholesalers shifted from gloom in August to
optimism last month. The balance of companies reporting an increase in sales
jumped to plus 49 points last month from plus 11 points in August.
Motor traders reported 'reasonable' sales growth last month after August's
strong increase, with sales of parts and accessories growing faster than
vehicle sales.
