<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Chief executive of Welsh agency resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHIEF EXECUTIVE of the Welsh Development Agency, Mr Philip Head,
resigned last night on the eve of the government's response to a highly
critical report about the agency by the Commons public accounts committee.
Mr Head has been chief executive of the government-funded agency since
January 1991. His resignation is one of a number of sweeping changes in the
management structure which are expected to be announced today.
Mr Head told the board he wanted to resign to 'enable a totally fresh
approach to be taken to the management of the agency'. He felt this would be
in its best interests. He will remain in the post until a replacement has
been found.
The report into the agency's accounts for 1991-92, which was published in
July, questioned the accountability of the agency and said poor management
practices had developed both in personnel matters and financial control.
Standards had fallen 'well below' what parliament had a right to expect. The
MPs called on the Treasury and Welsh Office to take urgent steps to ensure
the problems did not recur.
The report led to the agency's new chairman, Mr David Rowe-Beddoe, setting
up an internal inquiry under Sir John Caines, formerly permanent secretary
at the Department for Education. The findings of his inquiry are due to be
published today, and the response of Mr John Redwood, the Welsh secretary,
is also expected.
Mr Rowe-Beddoe, a businessman from the private sector who took over as
chairman from Dr Gwyn Jones, will detail the measures being taken by the
agency's board in the light of the public accounts committee report and the
Caines inquiry. It is likely that the management structure will be revamped
and some senior executives, in addition to Mr Head, are seen as vulnerable.
Mr Head, who is in his early 40s, joined the agency in 1978, only two years
after it was set up. Mr Rhodri Morgan, Labour MP for Cardiff West, said last
night: 'I bear Mr Head no ill-will, but his departure is part of the
long-needed root and branch overhaul of the WDA to bring it back to
political and financial respectability.'
The MPs' report criticised, among other matters, an unauthorised redundancy
scheme which incurred a loss of Pounds 1.4m, a scheme for free private
motoring for senior executives, the appointment of a fraudster as a
marketing director, and an apparent attempt to conceal the so-called
Operation Wizard to consider partial privatisation.
The MPs also blamed the Welsh Office for lack of supervision. Mr Redwood
said he took the criticisms very seriously and subsequently warned chairmen
of Welsh Office independent bodies that they must insist on the 'highest
standards of conduct'.
Mr Rowe-Beddoe, who was appointed the agency's chairman on July 1, promised
'appropriate remedial action' following the accounts committee report.
</TEXT>
