<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Clarke faces cabinet tax pleas today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH Clarke will today face calls from cabinet colleagues to avoid
jeopardising the apparently faltering economic recovery by imposing large
tax increases in next month's Budget.
But a full-scale cabinet debate of the options for November 30 will also
hear a warning from the chancellor that the government's borrowing
requirement is still on course to reach a record Pounds 50bn this year.
Mr Clarke will tell his colleagues that, despite the latest disappointing
output statistics, the economy should still grow faster this year than the
1.25 per cent predicted in March. Inflation will be lower than the 3.75 per
cent envisaged by Mr Norman Lamont, his predecessor.
His cautious optimism, however, will not extend to the outlook for the
borrowing requirement, leaving open the real prospect of further tax
increases. Mr Clarke has stressed repeatedly that the medium-term path for
borrowing set out by Mr Lamont will not restore the Treasury's finances
quickly enough.
But as MPs returned to Westminster yesterday after the summer break, cabinet
colleagues said that large tax increases in addition to the Pounds 10bn
annual increase announced by Mr Lamont would endanger the fragile economic
upturn.
Only a small minority of rightwing ministers - most notably Mr John Redwood,
the Welsh secretary - want the chancellor to resist any further rise in
taxation. But others were last night scaling back their views of what would
be an 'acceptable' pack-age.
One senior minister said unless the economy showed stronger signs of growth,
additional tax rises of more than Pounds 2bn or Pounds 3bn would risk a
backlash from Conservative MPs.
That assessment was echoed by another member of the cabinet who suggested
that Mr Clarke should be aiming for a 'symbolic' rather than substantial cut
in borrowing until the recovery was firmly established.
Others, however, believe that the chancellor could opt for phased increases
of about Pounds 5bn if the package was accompanied by a reduction in
interest rates of at least 1 percentage point.
Spending lifts PSBR, Page 12
</TEXT>
