<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Government insolvency unit slammed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S insol-vency service is failing to disqualify enough
directors of collapsed companies, says a highly critical National Audit
Office report to be released tomorrow.
The audit office, the watchdog on government spending and efficiency, calls
for greater efforts by officials to debar from future directorships
executives who have been responsible for the failure of their companies. The
report says the insolvency service, part of the Department of Trade and
Industry, has failed to prosecute many directors criticised by official
receivers and by private-sector insolvency practitioners appointed as
receivers and liquidators.
The insolvency service gained powers to bring prosecutions under the 1986
Directors' Disqualification Act, which allows the courts to suspend
individuals from holding directorships. In 1992-93, 651 directors were
disqualified against a total of 450 in 1991-92.
But the audit office estimates that only half of the cases against directors
identified by practitioners or the service's own staff as candidates for
disqualification have been pursued for prosecution.
It also highlights considerable variations by the regional offices of the
service in pursuing directors for disqualification.
The attack comes when record numbers of companies have failed and insolvency
practitioners within accounting firms have been expressing concerns that
their recommendations are not being pursued hard enough by the service.
The insolvency service - often supported by practitioners - has argued in
the past that its failure to disqualify more directors reflects insufficient
funding.
That concern led to a 9 per cent budget and staffing increase in the
insolvency service approved by ministers during the current year. The audit
office's report calls for greater publicity for the penalties of
disqualification and of those who have been prosecuted. A survey it
conducted of company directors showed that half were not even aware of the
existence of the legislation and its penalties.
It also criticises provisions within Scottish insolvency legislation which
allow companies without any assets to be dissolved without the option for
scrutiny of directors.
</TEXT>
