<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Wall St firms agree contributions ban: Self-imposed step
will have impact on future local elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HAVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of 15 of Wall Street's most powerful investment banking and
securities firms have agreed to stop making political contributions to US
government officials and election candidates who could award them contracts
to underwrite issues of local government securities.
The agreement on the voluntary ban, which has earned the support of the
Securities and Exchange Commission, was officially unveiled at the SEC in
Washington yesterday.
The group, including industry leaders Merrill Lynch, Smith Barney Shearson,
Goldman Sachs and Salomon Brothers, urged law firms, accountants, financial
advisers and other companies involved in the municipal finance process to
join the ban. A leading New York law firm, Skadden Arps, was part of
yesterday's pact.
Wall Street has been considering ending political contributions related to
the municipal bond business for over a year, but publicity surrounding
several recent political scandals helped persuade the firms to reach early
agreement.
No criminal action has been taken over any of the recent scandals, but they
reinforced the assumption among many voters that some Wall Street firms may
have been making financial contributions to local politicians in the hope of
bond underwriting business worth millions of dollars.
Yesterday's signatories said they hoped their initiative would restore
public confidence in the municipal securities market.
The ban will have a considerable impact on future local elections across the
US, because securities and investment banking firms have traditionally been
among some of the biggest financial backers of city and state politicians
campaigning for public office.
Mr Arthur Levitt, SEC chairman, said he remained concerned that some firms
might try to use political contributions by consultants, affiliates or
employees to attempt to influence municipal finance decision-making.
The ban should soon be backed by a new federal regulation proposed by the
Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board. It is expected to come into effect
later this year or early 1994.
</TEXT>
