<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / Georgian rebels make fast advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TBILISI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FORCES fighting for the return to power of the former Georgian president, Mr
Zviad Gamsakhurdia, have advanced rapidly to within 20km of Kutaisi, the
country's second city, with a population of 300,000.
It is the last centre in western Georgia still in the hands of the Georgian
government headed by Mr Eduard Shevardnadze. Mr Shevardnadze said in a
broadcast yesterday that his army 'has practically disintegrated'.
His senior ministers have been negotiating with Russian officials, and
unconfirmed reports say Russia has agreed to supply advanced military
technology to defend Kutaisi, including heavy artillery.
In an interview with the Financial Times at his base in Zugdidi in the west
of the country, Mr Gamsakhurdia said that 'this conflict will be settled and
Georgia will be cleansed of them (Mr Shevardnadze's supporters)'. Mr
Gamsakhurdia, who was deposed in a coup in January 1992, said he would
resume his 'lawful presidency' by 'all possible means'.
Early on Sunday morning, after it was clear the rapid military assault was
succeeding, Mr Loti Kobalia, Mr Gamsakhurdia's military commander, stood on
the balcony of the building occupied by the former president and whipped up
his supporters to frenzied cheering as he shouted: 'Victory is ours. . .
soon we will be in Kutaisi.'
Mr Gamsakhurdia, who has been in Georgia for one month after almost two
years' exile in the north Caucasian Russian republic of Chechnya, ruled out
negotiations with Mr Shevardnadze or any of his associates.
He said that Mr Jaba Josseliani, leader of the Mekhedrioni group of
irregular forces and effectively Georgia's chief-of-staff, was 'a four times
convicted criminal. . . He will make an agreement and break it at once.'
Mr Gamsakhurdia denies that he is prosecuting a civil war.
'You must not call it a civil war, it is a fight against criminal gangs,' he
said.
The former president's refusal to negotiate and the higher morale of his
forces, which are estimated to number about 10,000, means the country of
5.5m people now faces the prospect of a longer and more intense conflict.
Already Mr Vladizlav Ardzinba, leader of the Abkhazian separatists, has said
his republic will be an independent state equal to Russia and Georgia. Its
borders would be between the rivers Psou in the north and Incuri in the
south, cutting off around 15 per cent of former Georgian territory.
The offensive by Mr Gamsakhurdia's forces overran the rail junction of
Samtredia and the town of Khoni on Sunday after a few hours' resistance from
the scattered defenders. Their advance of some 25km towards Kutaisi
demonstrates the weakness of the Georgian forces which, apart from the
Mekhedrioni irregulars, are composed of national guardsmen and militia.
</TEXT>
