<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / London commuters hit by 6% rise in rail and Tube fares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAVELLERS face fare increases in the new year averaging 6 per cent on
London Transport, Network SouthEast and Scotrail services - but most
InterCity ticket prices will remain the same, it was announced yesterday.
After pressure from Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, plans for
double-figure rises - outlined in British Rail documents leaked this summer
 -were all but abandoned by operators.
The increases are three times the rate of retail price inflation and will
affect London commuters particularly hard.
The cost of the capital's popular, unlimited-use Travelcards will rise by up
to 10 per cent as London Transport attempts to bring them closer to their
travel value. A weekly one-zone Travelcard will cost Pounds 10.20 next
January, compared with Pounds 9.30 previously. A two-zone underground
journey will rise by 10p to Pounds 1.30.
Network SouthEast - which was earlier rumoured to be planning increases of
up to 16 per cent - responded to government pressure to keep its average
fare rises well below double figures.
The average rise for season tickets on most of the network's routes will be
6 per cent, but higher on better-performing lines such as Chiltern and West
Anglia. Following Citizen's Charter policy, the network's rises on
poorer-performing Kent Coast and Thames routes will be lower, at 3 per cent.
Off-peak fares will rise by 4 per cent.
Mr John Nelson, the network's managing director, emphasised that the average
rise would not be enough to overcome the 'very serious financial situation'
stemming from the 100,000 fall in the number of BR commuters and a drop in
property sales.
InterCity, which receives no subsidy, increased only its standard open
ticket fares by an average of 3 per cent.
Passenger groups criticised the fare rises for outstripping inflation and
the government for failing to deliver enough funding.
The London Regional Passengers' Committee said the government had placed BR
and LT in an 'impossible position' by depriving them of funds and of powers
to impose higher fare increases. It called on the government to allocate
sufficient funds in the November Budget to enable BR and LT to maintain
their transport systems and operate them safely.
Mr Michael Patterson, secretary of the Central Transport Consultative
Committee, the rail users' watchdog, said: 'Increases on some lines of up to
four times the rate of inflation are unprecedented and this will do nothing
to reverse the huge drop in rail commuting over recent years.'
Tory rail rebels warn government, Page 14
</TEXT>
