<HEADLINE>
FT  19 OCT 93 / George Michael's counsel sings the Sony blues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Justice Jonathan Parker is not the sort of judge who asks: 'Who is George
Michael?'
First, because the singer was sitting in front of him in the High Court in
London yesterday, clad in black T-shirt, black suit and designer stubble,
listening to his counsel argue that his contract with Sony should be
declared unenforceable.
Second, Mr Justice Parker, 55, would not play the game. Mr Mark Cran QC,
George Michael's lawyer, came up with enough pop icons to stump a dozen high
court judges, but Mr Justice Parker nodded knowingly. Madonna, Elton John,
even Holly Johnson of Frankie Goes to Hollywood - he knew them all.
Mr Cran said the singer's last few years had not been easy. His contract has
not made him as rich as some people thought.
In the five years to the end of 1992, George Michael's gross profits were a
mere Pounds 7.35m. Sony's gross profits from his recordings for the same
period were Pounds 52.45m.
The singer's profits were calculated after he had met recording costs
himself, as required by his contract, but before he had paid his
accountants, or - Mr Cran expressed regret - his lawyers.
George Michael had four barristers to represent him, including two QCs. The
second QC was Mr Jeremy Lever, who had come to argue that the contract was
in breach of European competition law and should be declared void. This
would result in the copyright to George Michael's songs being returned to
him. Time ran out before Mr Lever's turn came, so he spent the day puffing
on his Biro as if it were a stress-reducing accessory.
Mr Cran's job was to argue that the contract represented an unreasonable
restraint of trade and should be declared unenforceable. Its duration was
particularly onerous. Although it ends, in theory, in 2003, Mr Cran argued
that it could continue for longer, as George Michael would be liable for
damages if he had not delivered the six albums still required by his
contract.
An additional injustice was that Sony could reject albums if it was
dissatisfied with their contents. Mr Cran said this gave Sony the right to
make a subjective decision about artistic quality. It would be difficult for
a court to question that judgment. 'That's very true,' Mr Justice Parker
said, acknowledging a rare musical limitation.
George Michael had decided he wanted to be a serious musician rather than a
sex symbol. Sony had not given him support.
His fans did, though. Dewy-eyed, they sat in the public gallery, one in a
recklessly low-cut blouse, ready to endure hours of argument for their
serious musician. Most did not budge as Mr Cran explained the workings of
withholding tax.
The few who left paused to bestow upon their idol a look of tender
solicitude. As well they might; the case is likely to continue for 12 weeks.
</TEXT>
